  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "philosophy_depth",
      "score": 3,
      "finding": "All 6 principles are generic labels with one-line restatements, not actionable philosophy. 'Skills Are Training' explained as 'Knowledge as loadable modules' tells an agent nothing about how to think or make decisions. 'Continuous Refinement' described as 'Always improving' is a platitude applicable to any role in any company. None of the principles address the Skill Developer's specific tension: capturing tacit expert knowledge in a structured format that a non-expert AI can reliably execute.",
      "example_rewrite": "| **Tacit-to-Explicit Conversion** | When an SME says 'you just know when X is right,' that's your primary extraction target. Push for concrete decision rules: 'Under what conditions? What does failure look like? What would a newcomer miss?' Never publish a skill that relies on unstated intuition. | | **Load-Time Precision Over Comprehensiveness** | A skill file that is 3,000 words covering 90% of cases outperforms a 10,000-word file covering 99%. Agents load skills at task time — cognitive overhead is a real cost. Ruthlessly cut anything an agent cannot act on in the next 10 minutes of work. | | **Accuracy Degrades; Build in Expiry** | Every skill file has a domain half-life. Tag each file at creation with a review trigger: a date, a software version, or a process milestone. A skill without an expiry date is a liability, not an asset. |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "handoff_specificity",
      "score": 4,
      "finding": "Handoff tables name roles but describe artifacts in vague category labels ('Skill requirements', 'Domain knowledge', 'Skill files'). There is no specification of artifact format, file naming convention, where artifacts live in the repository, or what constitutes a complete vs. incomplete handoff. 'Skill files' delivered to Agent Onboarding Specialist and Role Engineer are the same label with no differentiation. The Role Engineer handoff direction is also contradictory — the table shows Skill Developer both receives 'skill needs' from Role Engineer AND delivers 'skill references' back, but neither artifact is defined.",
      "example_rewrite": "| Delivers To | Artifact | Format | Location | Complete When | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | Role Engineer | Skill reference manifest | `skill-manifest.md` listing skill filename, domain, version, load trigger phrase | `/skills/published/` | Role Engineer can add `loads: [skill-name.md]` to a role file without asking a follow-up question | | Agent Onboarding Specialist | Validated skill package | Zip of skill `.md` file + `skill-meta.yaml` (version, owner, expiry, test prompt) | `/skills/releases/` | Meta file passes schema validation; test prompt demonstrates correct agent behavior | | Quality Assurance Auditor | Skill review request | `skill-review-request.md` with skill file, test transcript showing agent output, and self-assessment against Skill Quality rubric | `/skills/pending-review/` | Auditor can begin review without requesting additional context |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 1,
      "finding": "There is no Anti-Patterns section in this role file. The template standard explicitly requires 3-5 role-specific anti-patterns. The Boundaries section lists DON'T items, but these are ownership boundaries ('don't create role templates'), not anti-patterns — they describe what the role should avoid doing, not failure modes in how the role performs its actual work. There is zero guidance on common ways a Skill Developer fails at skill development itself.",
      "example_rewrite": "## Anti-Patterns\n\n| Anti-Pattern | What It Looks Like | Why It Fails |\n|---|---|---|\n| **The Encyclopedia Skill** | Writing a skill file that covers every edge case, exception, and historical context of a domain | Agents load the entire file into context. A 6,000-word skill on financial modeling crowds out task-specific instructions and degrades output quality. Cap skills at 1,500 words; split large domains into composable sub-skills. |\n| **The Assumed Expert** | Writing skill content at the level of the SME who provided it, using jargon without definition | The loading agent is not the SME. If the skill says 'apply standard GAAP treatment' without defining what that means in this context, the agent will hallucinate a definition. Write for a competent generalist, not a domain specialist. |\n| **Single-Source Capture** | Building a skill file from one SME interview or one document | One expert's model is one expert's model. Validate against a second source or a real task transcript before publishing. Single-source skills fail silently — agents use them confidently and produce subtly wrong outputs. |\n| **Version Orphaning** | Publishing skill v1.1 without updating role files that reference v1.0 | Role files load skills by filename. If you rename or version a skill file without notifying the Role Engineer, deployed agents silently load stale knowledge. Always file a skill update notification to Role Engineer on any breaking change. |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "ai_deployment_clarity",
      "score": 4,
      "finding": "The Context Requirements section — the most critical section for an AI agent loading this role — contains literal placeholder text: '[Context item 1]' and '[Context item 2]'. The Required Skills table has no entries, only a format hint. This means an AI agent loading this role has no idea what context files to request, what skills to load, or what state it needs to be in before beginning work. The Iteration Protocol exists and is correctly structured, but it is generic (identical wording could appear in any Hybrid role). The workflow STOP points exist but do not specify who approves each stop or what approval looks like.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Required Context\n- [ ] Organizational Charter (to verify referenced roles exist before writing skill references)\n- [ ] Skill Standards Guide v1.x (current format specification for all skill files)\n- [ ] Skill Library Index (`/skills/index.yaml`) — confirms skill doesn't duplicate existing asset\n- [ ] SME Interview Notes or source document for the target domain\n- [ ] Quality rubric (`skill-quality-rubric.md`) — used in self-assessment before handoff to QA Auditor\n\n### Required Skills\n| Skill | When to Load |\n|---|---|\n| knowledge-extraction-techniques.md | Load before any SME interview or source document review |\n| skill-file-formatting-standard.md | Load before beginning any DEVELOP phase |\n| prompt-testing-methodology.md | Load before VALIDATE phase to structure agent test prompts |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "story_portal_relevance",
      "score": 1,
      "finding": "There is no Story Portal section in this role file. The template standard explicitly requires a Story Portal section that is project-relevant and specific. This is a complete omission, not a quality issue — the section does not exist at all. Given that the Skill Developer's output (skill files) is likely the foundational input that Story Portal agents load to perform narrative and domain tasks, this is particularly consequential. The absence means there is no guidance on how this role's outputs connect to the Story Portal product context.",
      "example_rewrite": "## Story Portal\n\n### Role in Story Portal Context\n\nSkill files created by this role are the primary mechanism by which Story Portal agents acquire specialized knowledge. Every story domain, genre convention, narrative technique, and editorial standard that agents apply originates as a skill file developed here.\n\n### Story Portal-Specific Skill Domains\n\n| Skill Domain | Loading Agents | Priority |\n|---|---|---|\n| Narrative structure frameworks (three-act, hero's journey, kishōtenketsu) | Story Architect, Chapter Writer | High |\n| Genre conventions by category (thriller, literary fiction, romance, etc.) | Chapter Writer, Story Critic | High |\n| Character psychology and voice differentiation | Character Developer, Dialogue Editor | High |\n| Editorial standards (show-don't-tell, pacing, POV consistency) | Story Critic, Continuity Editor | Medium |\n| World-building consistency rules | World Builder, Continuity Editor | Medium |\n\n### Story Portal Constraints\n- Skill files for Story Portal must include at least 3 annotated examples drawn from published fiction, not invented examples\n- All narrative technique skills must specify which story genres the technique applies to and which it conflicts with\n- Skills loaded by multiple Story Portal agents must be tested against each loading agent's primary workflow before publishing"
    }
  ],
  "top_improvement": "Add the Anti-Patterns section immediately — this is a complete omission of a required template section, and its absence means AI agents operating in this role have no failure-mode awareness. Unlike the placeholder Context Requirements (which signals incompleteness) or the missing Story Portal section (which reduces project relevance), the lack of anti-patterns actively increases the risk of the AI agent performing the role incorrectly without any self-correction signal. Write 3-4 anti-patterns specific to skill file creation failures: encyclopedic scope, assumed expert vocabulary, single-source capture, and version orphaning."
}
